Mother nature has been considered the most promising inspiration source for preparation of novel pharmacologically active chemical entities (

). Generally, natural compounds have been employed either in drug design processes or applied as starting scaffolds for structural modifications leading to the preparation of semisynthetic derivatives, which have demonstrated to be even more potent and/or less toxic in comparison with their parent structures (

; Simao et al., 2016).

Nowadays, 
in silico
methods have become noticeable during the development of novel drugs, and quantitative-structure activity relationship (QSAR) studies have been employed to identify important chemical features and consequently propose descriptors related with the respective biological activity, thus assisting in the discovery of novel potential lead compounds (

; 

). In fact, QSAR has been considered an important tool in the rational development and discovery of new drugs (

; 

).

Among a plethora of bioactive natural compounds, kaurenoic acid (
1
; 
ent
-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid; 
Fig. 1
), a kaurane-type diterpene, is found in high amounts in some Brazilian medicinal plants genera such as 

Copaifera

and 
Mikania
(

; Simao et al., 2016). Compound 
1
, in particular, has demonstrated to possess a wide spectrum of biological activities, displaying anti-inflamatory, analgesic, antispasmodic, antimicrobial, and antiparasitic activities (Batista et al., 2013; 

; 

; Tirapelli et al., 2005). Moreover, this diterpene has also attracted considerable attention from the scientific community because this natural compound and its structural derivatives exhibit significant 
in vitro
cytotoxic effects against several tumor cell lines (Batista et al., 2013; 

; 

; Simao et al., 2016).

As established in the scientific literature, microbial transformation is an area of great interest to the pharmaceutical and chemical industries, once it allows for the production of derivatives that are difficult to obtain by organic synthesis (

; 

). Biotransformation studies of natural products using 

Aspergillus
species

are commonly found in the scientific literature and hydroxylation is the major reaction produced by these microorganisms (

; 

; 

).

It is also noteworthy to mention that 2 is the main metabolite obtained by microbial transformation of 1 using
A. terreus
, a bioreaction that displayed a significant conversion yield (24.3%). This result is important, once ent -7α-hydroxy-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid ( 2 ) can be used as substrate for chemical and microbiological synthesis of gibberellins (
), a group of tetracyclic diterpenes that has agricultural applications due to their effects on plant growth (
).

QSAR studies were performed using the compounds obtained from the microbial transformation study ( 2 , 3 , 4 , 5 and 6 ), derivatives from kaurenoic acid previously reported in the literature (
; Simao et al., 2016) and two diterpenes constituents of our chemical standard set ( 7 and 8 ). These compounds are shown in Fig. 1 and the IC50 and p IC50 values employed in the QSAR analyses are depicted in Table 1 . The biological results are well spread into the range of 3.06–5.11 for p IC50 values ( Table 1 ), indicating that the data set is adequate for a QSAR study (
).

The resulting statistical parameters attend the minimum acceptable values for regression models in QSAR and satisfy the following conditions: Q 2> 0.5, R 2> 0.6 (
; Tropsha et al., 2003) and the difference between R 2 and Q 2 does not exceed 0.2–0.3, according to OECD (
) and Ericksson and coworkers (
). For the model proposed in this work, R2 – Q 2 = 0.08. The Pearson correlation coefficients between all descriptors and between descriptors and biological activity are exhibited in Table S2 (Supplementary information), together with the auto-scaled regression coefficients. The signals of the Pearson coefficients are in agreement with the signals from the regression coefficients, showing that the final PLS model is self-consistent and does not suffer from sign change problem (
). In addition, the low correlation between the variables shows that there is no information redundancy occurrence.

External validation of the proposed PLS model was carried out using a test set consisting of compounds 10 , 15 , 23 , 24 and 25 ( Fig. 1 ). The results ( Table 2 ) showed high prediction power, with the determination coefficient for external validation R 2 pred of 0.89 and the average relative error of prediction ( ARE pred) of 6.40. The obtained R 2 pred was much higher than the R 2 pred> 0.5 recommended value by Pratim and Kunal and Roy and coworkers (
;
).

The highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO), known as frontier orbitals, play an important role in the reactivity of molecules, considering the interaction between the outermost electrons of HOMO and the acceptor electron orbital, LUMO, of two reacting species. HOMO and LUMO energies are widely applied in drug-receptor interaction and structure-activity relationship studies (

; 

; 

; Silva et al., 2013; Zheng et al., 2013), as well as the difference between both (energy gap) that measures the molecule's stability. Molecules with a large energy gap present low chemical reactivity, while those with small energy gap can be easily excited favoring their bioactivity. In a drug-receptor system, the drug's HOMO interacts with the receptor's LUMO or vice-versa (Zheng et al., 2013).

The analysis and energies of HOMO‒1 and LUMO+1, the second highest occupied molecular orbital and the second lowest unoccupied molecular orbital, respectively, are usually also employed in structure-activity relationship studies. Braga and coworkers (

) studied the carcinogenic activity of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons through a theoretical approach based on the local density of electronic states and the energy separation values between HOMO and 
HOMO-
1 orbitals. The authors found that the activity of these compounds is related to the HOMO and HOMO‒1 energies, as well as to the difference between them. Bexarotene is an FDA-approved drug, currently in limited use for cutaneous manifestations of T-cell lymphomas (CTCL). Misra and coworkers (

) synthesized the prodrug version of bexarotene and performed DFT (density functional theory) calculations of molecular orbitals, such as HOMO, LUMO, 
HOMO-
1 and LUMO+1 energies, in order to investigate the possibility of using a reengineered form of the drug to treat hepatocellular carcinoma. Comparing the prodrug and drug, the calculation predicts the prodrug to be less cytotoxic and more stable than the drug. 
Ben
Hadda and coworkers (

) investigated the anti-tumor activity of rutheniumstaurosporine complexes through density functional theory (DFT)-derived reactivity indexes and their study indicated that the activity is closely related to the orbital energies, HOMO–1 and HOMO–1-LUMO +1 gap.

Among several electronic descriptors calculated in the present study, HOMO and HOMO- 1 energies were selected by the best PLS regression model and their coefficients, that were high in equation (1), suggesting that the interaction between the kaurenoic acid derivatives and the cell involves charge displacement and can occur by any kind of intermolecular interaction, even ionic or covalent bond. This finding seems to agree with the results from Duarte and coworkers (
) who pointed out that LUMO energies are an indicative of the interaction between the macrocyclic diterpenes and the receptor via charge transfer from the receptor to the diterpenes. The HOMO energy values for that study could not help understand the activity differences; however, the present QSAR analysis including twenty six diterpenes derived from kaurenoic acid elucidated the importance of HOMO orbital in the intermolecular interaction of this class of compounds. Although kaurenoic acid derivatives act as antiproliferative in MCF-7 breast cells (
), while the effect of macrocyclic diterpenes is to reverse the multidrug resistance (MDR) observed in tumor cells, both studies show that charge transfer plays an important role in cytotoxic activity displayed by this class of natural compounds.

In addition, Eq. (1) shows that lipophilic groups in the kaurenoic acid derivatives favor the biological activity due to log P value increase conferred by the substituent groups. This is also in agreement with the literature (
), where all studied diterpenes are lipophilic and the most active compounds present higher log P values. The kaurenoic acid derivatives results indicate that drug transport by the biological system where these compounds act is facilitated by lipophilicity increase. According to several authors (
;
,
; Wermuth et al., 2015), the absorption and distribution process of the pharmaceuticals are regulated by lipophilicity, as for the drug to achieve the target it requires to dissolve and penetrate biological membranes that form the tissues and systems of living organisms.

The biological response produced by bioactive compounds depends on a series of factors and conditions, including absorption and distribution mechanisms (
;
;
; Wermuth et al., 2015). The PLS model for this set of compounds indicate that HOMO and HOMO- 1 orbitals energies and log P are related to activity against MCF-7 breast cells. A careful analysis of the results revealed that the interaction of this series of diterpenes derived from kaurenoic acid can occur by charge displacement, mainly from diterpenes to the target. However, when comparing with results from the literature for other series of diterpenes, it is suggested that the interaction with the receptor can also occur by charge displacement from the target to the diterpenes. The PLS regression model also indicated that lipophilic substituents increase the biological activity. In addition, through visualization of the HOMO and HOMO- 1 molecular orbitals surfaces, it was possible to identify the positions in which the substituents should be modified in order to increase their biological activity. The graphical representations of these orbitals for active compounds suggest that the intermolecular interaction occurs mainly from substituent R1.

