Full geometry optimization and vibrational frequency calculations were carried out using the Gaussian09 program package (Gaussian Inc, Wallingford) using the B3LYP hybrid functional (
), and 6- 311 + G(d,p) basis set (
). The nature of the stationary point was determined through the eigenvalues obtained from the harmonic vibration analysis. The kaurenoic acid derivatives 2 to 26 were rotated around bonds a and b ( Fig. 5 ) in order to adopt the same conformation of optimized geometry as the most active molecule ( 1 ).

A total of 659 descriptors were obtained, including topological properties calculated by the e-Dragon software (Tetko et al., 2005). The partition coefficient octanol/water (log P ), molecular volume and surface area were calculated using the Hyperchem software version 7.0 (Hypercube, Gainsville). The calculated descriptors for the 26 compounds from the training and test sets ( Table 1 ) were organized in a matrix format X (26,659), while IC50 values were arranged in a column vector y , after data transformation into –log IC50 (or p IC50, with IC 50 in mol L −1). The auto-scaled (mean-centered and unity variance scales) y vector and descriptors matrix were correlated through the QSAR modeling software (
). Initially, those descriptors presenting a Pearson correlation coefficient with a p IC50 lower than 0.3 were eliminated (
). Then, the ordered predictors selection (OPS) algorithm (Teofilo et al., 2009), implemented on QSAR modeling, was applied during a second variable selection step. In the OPS algorithm, PLS models are built on auto-scaled descriptors by rearranging the columns of the data matrix in such a way that the most important descriptors are placed in the first columns. Then, successive PLS regressions are performed with increasing number of descriptors in order to find the best PLS model (
). Leave-one-out cross-validation was applied to determine the number of factors (latent variables) in the regression model.

The statistics of the final PLS model obtained, by taking into account the descriptors log 
P
, HOMO and 
HOMO-
1 energies, was assessed by the coefficient of multiple determination of calibration (R2), coefficient of multiple determination of cross validation, (
QLNO
2), standard error of calibration (
SEC
), standard error of cross validation (
SECV
) and average relative error of prediction (
ARE
pred) (Supplementary information, 
Table S3
). The final model obtained was validated applying y-randomization (

; 

) and leave- 
N
- out analyses. The y-randomization test was performed to investigate the possibility of chance correlation, where the y vector was scrambled 50 times. The robustness of the optimized model was examined by leave- 
N
- out cross validation (LNO, N = 1 to 5) procedure. This test was repeated twenty times for each N value, as explained by 

; 

; Baumann and Stiefl (2004) and 

(Baumann and Stiefl, 2004; 

; 

; 

).
